sec.p:
Only a doctrinal theological position escapes the extraordinary difficulties of definition and the dangers of misusing the idea of the common good. Within the space of a theological mode of thought, the recipients of the common good are human beings in general (as children of God). The temporal reference, at the individual level, is the single human life with its existential orientation toward salvation; at the collective level, the continuation of divine creation. And the substantive referent, as described by the papal encyclicals, is the ‘sum total of social conditions which allow people … to reach their fulfillment more fully and more easily’ (1965: Gaudium et Spes, encyclical no. 26
19
).
